               <sex cert="high">M</sex>
               <persName type="lemma">אלעזר</persName>
               <persName type="lemma" xml:lang="en">Eleazar</persName>–<state type="desc">
                  <note>Pedat (2)’s son</note>
               </state>
               <state type="provenance">
                  <note>bTaan25a<ref type="note" corresp="#d2e3716"/>(Kosowsky,Babylonico, 215-35)</note>
               </state>
               <state type="addl-Descr">
                  <note>–</note>
               </state>
               <floruit>3rdC<ref type="note" corresp="#d2e3742"/>
               </floruit>
               <note xml:id="d2e3716" n="61"> An amora by the name of ר' אלעזר (Eleazar [8]) is
                            mentioned often in PT (e.g. yBer 2:1, 4b) but
                            never as the son of a פדת. Thus he appears only in BT, and I assume he
                            is a different person. Hyman, Toldoth, 192,
                            claims that Eleazar ben Pedat was Babylonian, but does not bring clear
                            cut evidence for this. That he was the father of Pedat (1) S-H/M,
                            mentioned often in PT, is shown in yMeg 4:10,
                            75c. Thus I assume he is Palestinian.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e3742" n="62"> Was a contemporary of Rabbi
                            Ami (1), see Introduction 7.4.1.</note>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
